Data Accessing¶

a) Download and Load Data¶

The data is provided as a URL, thus any data scientist or collaborator can access it with an internet connection, rather than relying on a downloaded data set before running this file. The code below downloads the data set in its current state from github. Run the code below to download the data, and load it as a pandas data frame. Some entries are empty, which we replace with NaN values. The dataframe is stored as data.

In [ ]:
# download current snapshot of the data
url = [masked per original owners request] 
zipfile = ZipFile(io.BytesIO(urllib.request.urlopen(url).read()))
zipfile.extractall(path='.')

# data is saved as transactions.txt. parse it as a json
data = pd.read_json('transactions.txt', lines='transactions.txt')

# replace empty records with NaN
data = data.replace(r'^\s*$', np.nan, regex=True)

b) Number of Record and Fields¶

There are 786,363 transactions recorded. Each transaction is represented by 29 features, from account numbers to merchant names and card information. One of the features tells us if the transaction is fradulent.

c) Summary Statistics¶

There is some data preprocessing we need to do. For example, dates should be converted to datetime objects for more detailed summary statistics and provide opportunities for time series analysis for informed business decisions. The four features that can be converted to datetime objects are

  • transactionDateTime: date and time of the transaction
  • currentExpDate: expiration date of the card
  • accountOpenDate: date account was openned
  • dateOfLastAddressChange: last date when address changed

Additionally, we convert the following features to objects:

  • accountNumber: This is just an ID to identify the account
  • customerId: This is just an ID to identify the customer
  • cardCVV: This is a 3 digit code that functions as a passphrase
  • enteredCVV: Like cardCVV
  • cardLast4Digits: This is simply the last 4 digits of a credit card number

We treat the above as objects rather than numerical values because there is no concept of ordering. For example, a CVV of 301 is not considered greater than a CVV of 300, despite the CVV is represented numerically.

We address some findings from the data summaries, below.

In [ ]:
# converting the date columns to datetime objects

data['currentExpDate'] = pd.to_datetime(data['currentExpDate'], format='%m/%Y')

data['cardCVV'] = data['cardCVV'].astype(object)

Some quick notes:

  • accountNumber and customerId both have 5000 unique values. This suggests these columns may be related. Additionally, since there are 5245 unique last 4 digits of credit cards, then there must be customers who use more than one card to make transactions in this data set.

  • We suspect that accountNumber and customerId may be related and potentially duplicate since they have the same number of unique values, and intuitively, account number can serve as a unique indentifier for each customer. Likewise, merchantCountryCode and acqCountry might be majority the same since most transactions will happen where the merchant is in the country of acquisition, but since acqCountry has mostly missing values, we may consider removing that and keeping merchantCountryCode.

  • echoBuffer, merchantCity, merchantState, merchantZip, posOnPremises and recurringAuthInd are all 100% empty. These columns can be removed, since they provide no information for the data set.

  • The minimum of accountOpenDate should serve as a lower bound for all other dates in the data set. We confirm this, since the earliers accountOpenDate (given by the minimum) is the earliest date across the summary statistics of all the dates. dateOfLastAddressChange shares the same earliest date with accountOpenDate, however, overall, dateOfLastAddressChange is later than the accountOpenDate. These dates and elapsed times between dates of last address changes could potentially be informative when building a model to detect fraudulent transactions.

  • In addition to examining elapsed times, we can also look at other derived features, such as whether or not enteredCVV is the same as cardCVV.

  • There are 12 non-numeric, non-boolean, and non-datetime fields. These fields will be treated as factor variables. However, some of these fields have over 100 factors, and a few of these fields have over 1000 factors. During modelling, this could become memory intensive as we must one-hot encode these fields. Perhaps binning or feature engineering may be useful to reduce the number of factors.

  • For the numeric data, we can see that the mean and the median are not very close to each other, suggesting skewness. This could be indicative of the presence of outlier, or perhaps data collection errors.

b) Exploratory Analyses and Hypotheses¶

We are interested in uncovering structure that can help us identify fraudulent transactions. This can also serve as a feature engineering step if we discover interesting features to create. We propose to view the data set in three different manners. First, we look at the data from the account level, where we can examine transactions within accounts and observe if any transactions may be out of the ordinary for the account in question. We also explore transaction level data, where we examine qualities of transactions that may be indicative of fraud. Finally, we study how the store data is organized, and if there is any relationship between merchants and fraud.

Before we explore transaction and account level data, first, we should explore class imbalance. Naturally, we would expect fraud to be a rarer occurence in a compliant bank.

In [ ]:
fraud_count = modified_data['isFraud'].value_counts()
keys = ['Not Fraudulent', 'Fraudulent']
plt.pie(fraud_count, labels = keys, explode=[0, 0.1], autopct='%.2f%%')
plt.title('Percentage of Fraudulent Transactions within data')
plt.show()

We can see that the data set has a significant class imbalance. About 1.6% of the transactions are acutally fraudulent, while 98.4% of transactions are legitimate. A naive classifier would be correct 98.4% of the time, just be labelling everything as not fraudulent. Of course, such a model would not be very useful.

Account Level Explorations¶

We hypothesize the following. For a given account:

  • If an account makes a transaction that is significantly different from its previous non-fraudulent transaction amounts, it may be fraudulent.
  • If multiple and frequent transactions are made within a short time period, the account should be investigated
  • If an account is susceptible to fraud, as measured by the cumulative fraud rate up to the time of each transaction, then most recent transaction should be investigated.

i) Transaction amounts that differ from previous amounts might be fraudulent¶

If an account typically makes small transaction amounts, a transaction of a large amount could be fraudulent, since it is not ordinary for that account. However, if an account typically makes large purchases, a sudden purchase of a low amount may not be fraudulent. We explore this hypothesis below.

We consider a moving median over a quarterly basis, that is, we track the deviation of each transaction from the median of transaction amounts for the last 91 days prior to each transaction. To do so, we take each account, and evaluate the difference between a transaction amount, and its moving median with a 91 day look back. Then we examine how this difference compares between fraudulent and non-fraudulent transactions.

In [ ]:
# for each account, calculate a moving median (more robust than average). window size 91, quarterly
account_grouped = modified_data.groupby('accountNumber')
rolling_median = account_grouped['transactionAmount']
rolling_median = rolling_median.apply(lambda x: x.shift(1).rolling(window=91, min_periods=0).median())
rolling_median = rolling_median.reset_index(0,drop=True)
modified_data['difference_moving_median'] = modified_data['transactionAmount'] - rolling_median

sns.boxplot(x=modified_data['isFraud'], y=modified_data['difference_moving_median'])
plt.title('Difference in Transaction Amount from Median for Fraud and Non-Fraud Transactions')
plt.xlabel('Fraud')
plt.ylabel('Amount Difference from Median')
plt.show()

Our hypothesis that large transaction amounts that differ from the usual for an account, is more likely to be fraudulent, is confirmed by the barplots. In particular, transaction amounts that are much larger than usual, by at least $234 dollars more, are three times more likely to be fraudulent.

Conversely, transactions that are smaller than the account's ordinary, tend to not be more fraudulent.

ii) If multiple and frequent transactions are made within a short time period, the account should be investigated¶

Typical healthy acconuts would not make several transaction in a short period of time. We define a short period of time to be a minute. We mark all transactions that occur within 1 minute of the previous transaction as transactions occuring in a short period of time, and evaluate how many of them are fraudulent.

The intuition here is that some forms of fraud will repeatedly make transactions within a short (within seconds) period of time. To evaluate this, we take the time difference between each transaction after ordering it by account number and transaction date time. We flag a transaction a "short period" if the time difference is less than 1 minute. Then we evaluate the rate of fraudulent transactions in "short period" transactions and normal transactions.

In [ ]:
time_window = pd.Timedelta(minutes=1)
# calculate time since last transaction and time until next transaction
modified_data['time_since_prev_transaction'] = modified_data.groupby('accountNumber')['transactionDateTime'].diff()
modified_data['time_until_next_transaction'] = modified_data.groupby('accountNumber')['transactionDateTime'].diff(periods=-1).abs()

flag_multiple_transactions = ((modified_data['time_since_prev_transaction'] <= time_window) & 
                              (modified_data['time_until_next_transaction'] <= time_window)).astype(int)

multiple_transactions_df = modified_data.groupby(flag_multiple_transactions)['isFraud']
multiple_transactions_df = multiple_transactions_df.agg([("isFraud", "mean"), ("count", "count")])
multiple_transactions_df['isFraud'] = multiple_transactions_df['isFraud'] * 100

# Barplot of Flagged Multiple Transaction against isFraud
ax = sns.barplot(x=multiple_transactions_df.index, y=multiple_transactions_df.isFraud)
plt.title('Fraudulent Rates by Flagged Multiple Transactions')
plt.xlabel('Flagged Multiple Transactions')
plt.ylabel('Fraudulent Transaction Rate (%)')
plt.bar_label(ax.containers[0])
plt.plot()
Out[ ]:
[]

Based on the analysis, it appears that multiple transactions happening within a 1-minute time period could indicate fraudulent activity. The fraudulent rate of multiple transactions was found to be about 2 times higher compared to transactions that did not meet this time period constraint. Hence, incorporating this feature into our fraud detection system could be useful in detecting fraudulent transactions.

iii) Accounts with high cumulative fraud rates, up to the current transaction, tend to have fraudulent transactions again.¶

An account that is typically involved in fraud will likely be involved in future fraud. Either the account is a popular target for fraud, or it is actively commiting fraud. Regardless, we can implement this by taking each account, and sorting their transactions by time. Then calculate a cumulative fraud rate for each transaction. When we plot the cumulative fraud rate against whether or not the transaction was fraudulent, we would expect to see a higher fraudulent rate for accounts that have a history of fraud - if our hypothesis is supported by the data.

We evaluate this by taking a cumulative sum of fraudulent transactions for each account, as we iterate down a time ordered list of the account's transactions.

In [ ]:
# sort data by accountNumber and transactionDateTime
modified_data = modified_data.sort_values(['accountNumber', 'transactionDateTime'])

# per account, calculate the cumulative sum of fraud up to a current transaction, and the same for number of transactions
cumulative_fraud_count = modified_data.groupby('accountNumber')['isFraud'].cumsum()
cumulative_count = modified_data.groupby('accountNumber')['isFraud'].cumcount() + 1

# calculate the cumulative fraud rate up until the current transaction
cumulative_fraud_rate = cumulative_fraud_count / cumulative_count
modified_data['cumulative_fraud'] = cumulative_fraud_rate
# create a boxplot to visualize the difference in amount for fraud and non-fraud transactions
sns.violinplot(x=modified_data['isFraud'], y=cumulative_fraud_rate)
plt.title('Cumulative Fraud Rate for Fraud and Non-Fraud Transactions')
plt.xlabel('Fraud')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Fraud Rate')
plt.show()

We do see a marked difference in cumulative fraud rates. Fraudulent transactions are more likely to belong to accounts that have a history of fraudulent transactions. We note that this feature may be useful in our predictive model, but when a new account is added, our predictive model may yield false negatives, since we are cannot to keep track of a cumulative sum of fraudulent transactions on a brand new account - this is an unmeasurable event. Nonetheless, this finding can inform future feature engineering and data collection initiatives.

Transaction Level Explorations¶

Transaction level explorations tell us what qualities in a transaction make it more likely to be fraudulent.

We propose a few relationships that might be related to fraudulent transactions:

  • Relationship of fraud to merchant codes and transaction types: Are transactions with certain merchants common targets for fraud?
  • Relationship of fraud to transaction amounts: Are transactions typically high value or low valued in fraud?
  • Relationship of fraud to binary variables such as whether or not a card is present, or expiration date matches: Is a card being present associate whether or not a transaction is fraudulent?
  • Relationship of fraud to elapsed times: We have time variables on expirations, account opennings, and address changes. Does fraud depend on the ages of accounts, or how close they are to expiry, or if a recent address change leads to more frequent fraud?
  • Relationship of fraud to previous flagged cards or incorrectly entered CVV numbers: Do cards that have previously been involved with fraudulent transactions show up again? Do cards with incorrectly entered CVV numbers tend to be more fraudulent?

  • Card Present: The contingency table shows that fraudulent transactions are more common when the card is not present (0.75), compared to when the card is present (0.27). Fisher's exact test comes out to be significant, with a p-value of close to 0. This suggests that there is a statistically significant relationship between the card being present in a transaction, and whether or not the transaction is fraudulent.

  • Expiration Date Matching: This contingecy table shows no real difference between whether or not a transaction is fraudulent versus whether or not the expiration date matches. Fisher's exact test agrees with this insight, with a larger p-value of 0.45. That is, we have no evidence to suggest the expiration date matching is associated with fraud.

iv) Fraud versus Time Variables¶

We can investigated the potential link between fraudulent transactions and various time-based factors. These factors include: Time elapsed since:

  • Last address change
  • Account opening
  • Card expiration

To explore this connection, we calculate the following durations based on the transaction date and relevant date variables in the dataset:

In [ ]:

Store Level Findings¶

  • If a transaction amount at a merchant was flagged as fraudulent, then future transaction of the same amount and location should also be investigated for fraud
  • Merchant stores have multiple franchises and numbers to identify the franchise. There is no trend over franchise IDs and difference in fraudulent transactions.

Merchant names in the data set have different merchant store numbers. We could include all these in the data set, however it may result in a large data set and is intractable to deal with. Instead, we check if we can drop the store numbers, by making sure the fraud rates across chains are not too different. This is an important step since we do not want to cluster stores numbers that have different fraud profiles.

i) If a transaction amount at a merchant was flagged as fraudulent, then future transaction of the same amount and location should also be investigated for fraud¶

Typically a fraudulent transaction made at merchant will target multiple people. Usually, the amount frauded is the same for everyone. If an account was flagged for fraud at a particular location, we would expect other transactions at the same merchant for the same amount to be fraudulent.

In [ ]:

The analysis suggests that transaction that occur at the same merchants of the same amount, that were previously flagged for fraud, has shown to indicate more frequent fraudulent activity, by about 30 times. We may try to include this into our fraud detection system.

ii) There is no trend over franchise IDs and difference in fraudulent transactions.¶

In otherwords, we expect franchises to have the same distribution of fraudulent transactions, over all their franchises.

Feature Designing¶

a) Reversed Transaction¶

In order to identify reversed transactions, we should reasonably expect the following:

  1. The reverse transaction has the same amount as the original transaction
  2. The reverse transaction should belong to the same account number and merchant name
  3. The transaction type should be of type PURCHASE and then followed by a REVERSAL that happens after the purchase. The reversal does not need to be immediately after the purchase.
In [ ]:
modified_data = modified_data.sort_values(['accountNumber','transactionAmount','transactionDateTime'])

condition1 = (modified_data['transactionAmount'] == modified_data['transactionAmount'].shift(1))
condition2 = (modified_data['accountNumber'] == modified_data['accountNumber'].shift(1)) & (modified_data['merchantName'] == modified_data['merchantName'].shift(1))
condition3 = ((modified_data['transactionType'] == "REVERSAL") & 
              (modified_data['transactionType'].shift(1) == "PURCHASE"))

reversed_condition = (condition1 & condition2 & condition3)
reversed_select = (reversed_condition | reversed_condition.shift(-1))
# select the rows that meet the condition and the rows that follow them
reversed_df = modified_data.loc[reversed_select]

The dataset above contains pairs of purchases and reversals. To calculate the total value of reversed transactions, the durations, and averages, we treat each purchase and reversal pair as a group.

We can efficiently group transactions and assign unique IDs to each group using cumsum(), which is a neat trick since we can avoid looping over the data set. We negate the boolean conditions defined above, and keep track of a cumulative sum that sums over increments when the above conditions are NOT met. Thus when the conditions are not met, we continue to increment, but when we hit a purchase/reversal group, the cumsum does not increment. This running sum can be treated as a group ID.

In [ ]:
transaction_group_r = (~(reversed_condition)).cumsum()

# sum of reversed transactions
value_of_reversed = reversed_df.groupby(transaction_group_r).apply(
    lambda x: x['transactionAmount'].iloc[1:].sum()).sum()

# total count of reversed transactions
num_reversed = reversed_df.groupby(transaction_group_r).apply(lambda x: len(x)-1).sum()

# avg of reversed 
avg_value_reversed = value_of_reversed / num_reversed

# duration between purchase and reversal
avg_duration_seconds = reversed_df.groupby(transaction_group_r)['transactionDateTime']
avg_duration_seconds = avg_duration_seconds.diff().mean().total_seconds()
avg_duration_days = avg_duration_seconds // (24 * 3600)
avg_duration_hours = (avg_duration_seconds % (24 * 3600)) // 3600

print(f"The total dollar count of reversed transactions is: ${value_of_reversed}")
print(f"The total number of reversed transactions is: {num_reversed}")
print(f"The average transaction amount of reversed transactions is: ${round(avg_value_reversed, 2)}")
print(f"The average duration between reversed transaction pairs is: {int(avg_duration_days)} days, {int(avg_duration_hours)} hours")

The total dollar count of reversed transactions is: $2661859.55
The total number of reversed transactions is: 17704
The average transaction amount of reversed transactions is: $150.35
The average duration between reversed transaction pairs is: 10 days, 14 hours

b) Multi-swipe Transactions¶

Multiswipe transactions are transactions that occur multiple times in a short time frame of the same amount. This may happen as a fraudulent transaction, or as a mistake where the merchant processes a payment multiple times on accident. We identify the criteria with the following heuristics:

  1. The transaction amount has to be the same across adjacent transactions
  2. The transactions should be the same amount
  3. The transaction should happen in a short period of time, which we will say within 20 minutes.
  4. The transaction has to be from the same merchant and account number
  5. The transaction should be of type PURCHASE
In [ ]:
modified_data = modified_data.sort_values(['accountNumber','transactionDateTime'])

condition1 = (modified_data['transactionAmount'] == modified_data['transactionAmount'].shift(1))
condition2 = (modified_data['accountNumber'] == modified_data['accountNumber'].shift(1))
condition3 = (modified_data['merchantName'] == modified_data['merchantName'].shift(1))
condition4 = (modified_data['time_since_prev_transaction'] <= pd.Timedelta(seconds=1200))
condition5 = ((modified_data['transactionType'] == modified_data['transactionType'].shift(1)) & 
              (modified_data['transactionType'] == "PURCHASE"))
multi_swipe_condition = condition1 & condition2 & condition3 & condition4 & condition5
multi_swipe_select = (multi_swipe_condition | multi_swipe_condition.shift(-1))
# select the rows that meet the condition and the rows that follow them
multi_swipe_df = modified_data.loc[multi_swipe_select]

transaction_group_ms = (~(multi_swipe_condition)).cumsum()

# Calculate the total dollar count of reversed transactions
total_dollar_count = multi_swipe_df.groupby(transaction_group_ms)
total_dollar_count = total_dollar_count.apply(lambda x: x['transactionAmount'].iloc[1:].sum()).sum()

# Calculate the total number of reversed transactions
total_num_multi_txns = multi_swipe_df.groupby(transaction_group_ms).apply(lambda x: len(x)-1).sum()

# Calculate the average transaction amount of reversed transactions
avg_multi_txn_amount = total_dollar_count / total_num_multi_txns

print(f"The total dollar count of multi-swipe transactions is: ${round(total_dollar_count, 2)}")
print(f"The total number of reversed transactions is: {total_num_multi_txns}")
print(f"The average transaction amount of reversed transactions is: ${round(avg_multi_txn_amount, 2)}")

The total number of reversed transactions is: 7334
The average transaction amount of reversed transactions is: $148.0

From these plots, we see that reversed and multiswipe transactions are more likely to be fraudulent, albeit the difference is small. Ultimately, we will not know if a transaction is reversed, or is a multiswipe, until after the second transaction, where it may be a reversal, or another purchase of the same amount. While these features can clearly provide features for a fraud detection model, it would rely on data from the future, and is not a measurable event until at least after the second transaction occurs. Thus we cannot add this to our model, or we would suffer from data leakage.

d) Tying Up Loose Ends in Data Wrangling¶

We need to take extra care in examining if missing data in posConditionCode, transactionType, merchantCountryCode, and posEntryMode are related to fraudulent transactions. The absence of these data points can be valuable in determining what is fraudulent. That is, the absence of evidence is not the evidence of absence. Below, we compare:

In [ ]:
def get_mean_fraud_rate(data_name):
    missing = modified_data[data_name].isna()
    missing_mean = modified_data[missing]['isFraud'].mean()
    non_missing_mean = data[~missing]['isFraud'].mean()
    print(f"Mean fraud rate for missing {data_name}: {missing_mean:.2%}")
    print(f"Mean fraud rate for non-missing {data_name}: {non_missing_mean:.2%}")

Across the board, we observe that transactions that have missing values have a higher fraud rate than the transactions that do not have missing values. Thus we should create new features to handle these missing values. We call these values as 'Unknown', so that we know these values are unpopulated but meaningful.

In [ ]:
modified_data['posConditionCode'] = modified_data['posConditionCode'].fillna('Unknown')
modified_data['transactionType'] = modified_data['transactionType'].fillna('Unknown')
modified_data['merchantCountryCode'] = modified_data['merchantCountryCode'].fillna('Unknown')
modified_data['posEntryMode'] = modified_data['posEntryMode'].fillna('Unknown')

Models¶

In order to pass factor variables into a model, we consider turning them into dummy variables, that will be treated as one-hot encoded variables. We do this for our categorical features. Additionally, some of our time variable still have missing values. We interpolate the missing values, and convert datetime objects into seconds.

In [ ]:
cat_cols =['merchantCountryCode','posEntryMode','posConditionCode','merchantCategoryCode','transactionType','truncated_merchant']
one_hot_df = pd.get_dummies(modified_data.loc[:, cat_cols], drop_first=True)
modeling_df = pd.concat([modified_data.drop(cat_cols, axis=1), one_hot_df], axis=1)

modeling_df['difference_moving_median'] = modeling_df['difference_moving_median'].interpolate()
modeling_df['time_since_prev_transaction'] = modeling_df['time_since_prev_transaction'].dt.total_seconds()/ (60*60*24)
modeling_df['time_until_next_transaction'] = modeling_df['time_until_next_transaction'].dt.total_seconds()/ (60*60*24)
modeling_df['time_since_prev_transaction'] = modeling_df['time_since_prev_transaction'].fillna(0)
modeling_df['time_until_next_transaction'] = modeling_df['time_until_next_transaction'].fillna(0)

modeling_df['previous_fraud'] = modeling_df['previous_fraud'].astype(bool)

Now we begin our train and test split. We split by account number, to ensure that all transactions beloning to a single account stay in the same side of the split to prevent data leakage. As we have discovered that the response variable isFraud is highly imbalanced, we should think of a way to handle the class imbalance so as to not bias the model towards rating everything as not fraudulent. Parallel to this, we also need to think about the speed and computational tractability of modelling. With over 700,000 data points, only about 11,000 data points are fraudulent. One way to handle the computational tractability issue, while also reducing the class imbalance, is to undersample.

In [ ]:
train_accounts, test_accounts = train_test_split(modeling_df['accountNumber'].unique(), test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
train_data = modeling_df[modeling_df['accountNumber'].isin(train_accounts)]
test_data = modeling_df[modeling_df['accountNumber'].isin(test_accounts)]

X_train = train_data.drop(['isFraud','accountNumber','transactionDateTime',
                           'merchantName', 'currentExpDate', 'accountOpenDate',
                           'dateOfLastAddressChange', 'enteredCVV', 'cardCVV', 
                           'cardLast4Digits'], axis=1)
y_train = train_data['isFraud']

X_test = test_data.drop(['isFraud','accountNumber','transactionDateTime',
                         'merchantName', 'currentExpDate', 'accountOpenDate',
                         'dateOfLastAddressChange', 'enteredCVV', 'cardCVV', 
                         'cardLast4Digits'], axis=1)
y_test = test_data['isFraud']

sampler = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=0x0badbeef)
X_sampled, y_sampled = sampler.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

Models Evaluated¶

We evaluate three models, Random Forest, XGBoost, and Gradient Boosting. These three models are some of the most popular, in part due to their simplicity and overall success in general supervised learning tasks.

  • Random Forest: A popular model in fraud detection since it handles non-linearities in a non-parametric fashion, as well as being resistent to overfitting. A random forest is constructed by training a large number of decision trees on randomly sampled subsets of predictors. Each tree produces a prediction and is averaged over all the trees to make a final prediction. This is a bagging type of classifier.

  • Gradient Boosting: This is another popular model that uses a boosting approach, as opposed to bagging like in random forests. The boosting approach starts with a weak classifier iteratively fits further trees to fit the residuals of the previous weaker classifier. This nature of training can be susceptible to overfitting, so we must consider using k-fold CV and picking optimal hyperparameters.

  • XGBoost: One way to combad the overfitting issue in Gradient Boosting is by regularization. XGBoost handles this with L2 regularization, where it discourages the weights in the model from growing too large. This can combat overfitting, since typically, overfitting is a product of a highly non-smooth parameter space, with certain parameters being large in value, learned from memorizing the data. The regularization term prevents this from happening by discouranging any one weight from becoming too large. This algorithm is also faster than gradient boosting.

As a final step, we ensemble these models. This allows us to leverage the benefits of the models above, while dampening the effects of each model's negative qualities.

Metric to Evaluate¶

We are trying to detect fraud. Ideally, we wish to be able to identify fraud 100% of the time, however this expectation is not realistic. Instead we must decide which type of mistakes our model makes, is more costly. If our model fails to identify fraud, when the transaction was actually fraudulent, as an organization, we may suffer damages and develop a bad reputation. This is worse than being overly cautious and potentially flagging legitimate transactions as fraudulent. Thus we choose to optimize to minimize false negatives, or maximize recall. Models with high recall are better at detecting fraud, when there in fact is fraud. Recall effectively measures the power, in the statistical sense, of a classifer.

Regarding hyperparameter tuning, we use Grid Search, to optimize for recall. We do not tune n_estimators since literature in predictive analytics suggests we should always use as many estimators are possible, provided the computational power can handle the load. Here, we use 200 estimators for all the models.

In [ ]:
models = {
    'XGBoost': XGBClassifier(),
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(),
    'Gradient Boosting': GradientBoostingClassifier()
}

parameters = {
    'XGBoost':  {'n_estimators': [200],'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 1.0]},
    'Random Forest': {'n_estimators': [200], 'max_depth': [5, 10, 20]},
    'Gradient Boosting': {'n_estimators': [200], 'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 1.0]}
}

# Train and evaluate each model using k-fold cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning
cv = 5
results = {}
best_models = {}
for name, model in models.items():
    param_grid = parameters[name]
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid, cv=cv, scoring='recall')
    grid_search.fit(X_sampled, y_sampled)
    results[name] = grid_search.best_score_
    best_models[name] = grid_search.best_estimator_

    print("Best recall score for {}:".format(name), results[name])
    print("Best model for {}:".format(name), best_models[name])

# define the metrics to evaluate

    'accuracy': 'accuracy',
    'recall': 'recall',
    'precision': 'precision',
    'f1': 'f1',
    'roc_auc': 'roc_auc'
}

# evaluate each model using cross-validation and store the results
results = {}
for name, model in models:
    cv_results = cross_validate(model, X_sampled, y_sampled, cv=cv, scoring=scoring, return_train_score=True)
    results[name] = cv_results

    # Print the confusion matrix
    y_pred = cross_val_predict(model, X_sampled, y_sampled, cv=cv)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_sampled, y_pred)
    print(name + ' confusion matrix:')
    print(cm)

From the model results, all models very well, with recall scores greater than 80%. Overall, we do not see any issues with overfitting, as the train and test metrics are about the same across the models. XGBoost and the ensemble model have the highest overall performance across all metrics when evaluated on the test set, which the model has not seen before.

As XGBoost and the ensemble model have similar recall scores, I would recommend use of the XGBoost model, since it is smaller in size than the ensemble method. XGBoost is a part of the ensemble, and the addition of random forest and gradient boosting in the ensemble yields marginal benefits.

Feature Importances¶

Having selected XGBoost as the preferred model, we can determine its feature importances. By analyzing feature importance, we can uncover the key relationships that influence the model's predictions. This knowledge not only enhances our understanding of the problem but also informs future data collection and feature engineering strategies.

8 of our engineered features turned out to be in the top 20 most important features. The top 3 most important features are:

  • cumulative_fraud: How many transactions has this account had, that have been flagged before?
  • transactionAmount: the amount of the transaction
  • difference_moving_median: If a transaction amount is significantly different from its previous transaction amounts

Two of these three features are products of our feature engineering.

The feature posEntryMode_05 is also important. This finding can drive future modifications in protocol to help curb fraudulent activity in these types of points of sale.

Future Directions¶

In practice, I would spend more time tuning the models above, using a train set which is to be partitioned into a train and validation set. This would take more time but reduce further risks of data leakage. In the current method, we suffer some data leakage due to cross validation occuring on future data sets. This happens because in k-fold CV, we might train based on future transactions to evaluate the hold out set containing transaction that occured in the past. To solve this problem, we would consider implementing a time series cross validation.

Some alternative methods that have been proven to work in other domains are network analytics, and reinforcement learning. Both methods approach the problem in a different manner, and addresses a critical flaw in classical predictive analytics: time and data dependencies.

Network Analysis¶

Merchants and customers transactions can be represented as a bipartite network, where transactions are edges, and edges connect merchants to customers. We can perform edge classification to determine whether or not a transaction is fraudulent. Due to the nature of network data, this method allows us to identify accounts or merchants that are at the center of fraudulent transactions. The steps for this type of analysis are as follows:

  • Define each node as either a merchant or an account. Draw an edge if a transaction has occured between them, and weight it by the number of transactions
  • Measure centrality metrics to identify "popular" merchants. We can perform several data explorations at this point
  • Encode the network and perform supervised learning on the network

Reinforcement Learning.¶

Additionally, we can approach this problem from a reinforcement learning perspective. The benefits of this method allow for online experimentation, wherein each new data point trains the model, and we do not need to rely on a hold out test set to evaluate our model. In particular, Q-learning allows us to consider time dependencies, which is a big drawback to current predictive analytics methods, where there are IID assumptions in the models. The steps of this type of analysis are as follows:

  • Define an agent to take in transaction data i.e. accountId, merchantName, other features we engineered in the project, and provide an action (fraud, not fraud)
  • Sort the transaction data by increasing order of time
  • As the agent iteratively moves down the transaction data, it updates its probabilities of taking a particular action through the classical Q learning algorithm

These methods could potentially yield better results and better generalizability than the predictive analyics approach we detailed in this project.
